\section{Sensitivity analysis to unmeasured confounding}
\label{sec:SensitivityFinal}

In this section, we present the sensitivity analysis results for the subset of covariates that yielded statistically significant bias bounds at the 5\% level, while omitting those that did not reach significance to ensure a clear signal.

\iffalse
\subsection{Bounds under additional parametric assumptions}

We explored several parametric assumptions for the bias bounds and report only the one that resulted in the smallest p-value for the effect of $\boldsymbol{\delta}$.

perturbations.original:
In the previous subsection, the bias bound depended on two sensitivity components, one governing the additional outcome variation explained by $\boldsymbol{U}$ and another governing how strongly $\boldsymbol{U}$ shifts the exposure law beyond $\boldsymbol{X}$. Here, we discuss additional assumptions that can sharpen these inferences. Specifically, recent work in \cite{zheng2021bayesian} shows that the exposure-side component can be partially identified under certain conditions when multiple treatments are available. For this, we assume the following data generating process for the unmeasured variables and the observed variables of interest:
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{U} &= \boldsymbol{\epsilon}_u \\
\boldsymbol{W} &= h(\boldsymbol{X}) + \boldsymbol{B}\boldsymbol{U} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon}_w \\
Y &= \mu(\boldsymbol{W}, \boldsymbol{X}) + \boldsymbol{\gamma}^{\top}\boldsymbol{U} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon}_y.
\end{align*}
\noindent Here $\boldsymbol{U}$ is an $m$-dimensional vector of unmeasured confounders, $\boldsymbol{B} \in \mathbb{R}^{q \times m}$, $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_u \sim N_m(0,\boldsymbol{I}_m)$, and $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_{w} \sim N_q(0, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{w\mid u})$ with $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{w\mid u}$ being a diagonal matrix. This model implies the conditional confounder distribution is
\begin{equation} \label{f_u|t}
f(\boldsymbol{u}\mid \boldsymbol{W}=\boldsymbol{w}, \boldsymbol{X}=\boldsymbol{x}) \sim N_m(\boldsymbol{\mu}_{u\mid w,x}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{u\mid w}),
\end{equation}
where
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{\mu}_{u\mid w,x}
&= \boldsymbol{B}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{B}\boldsymbol{B}^{\top}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{w\mid u})^{-1}\big(\boldsymbol{w}-h(\boldsymbol{x})\big), \\
\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{u\mid w}
&= \boldsymbol{I}_m - \boldsymbol{B}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{B}\boldsymbol{B}^{\top}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{w\mid u})^{-1} \boldsymbol{B}.
\end{align*}
Under fairly standard conditions in the factor analysis literature \citep{anderson1956statistical}, the matrix $\boldsymbol{B}$ is identifiable up to rotation, which identifies certain quantities relevant to a sensitivity analysis. For example, the partial $R^2$ between the unmeasured variable and a linear combination of the treatments $\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{W}$ is given by
$$
R^2_{\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{W} \sim \boldsymbol{U} \mid \boldsymbol{X}}
=\frac{\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{B}\boldsymbol{B}^{\top}\boldsymbol{a}}{\boldsymbol{a}^{\top} (\boldsymbol{B}\boldsymbol{B}^{\top} + \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{w\mid u}) \boldsymbol{a}},
$$
which is identified since the quantity $\boldsymbol{B}\boldsymbol{B}^{\top}$ is invariant to rotation. Further, under this framework with additive confounding by $\boldsymbol{U}$, we have a closed form expression for $d(\boldsymbol{X}, \boldsymbol{w})$, which is given by
$$
d(\boldsymbol{X}, \boldsymbol{w}) = \boldsymbol{\gamma}^{\top}\boldsymbol{\mu}_{u\mid w,x}.
$$
Our bias expression can therefore be simplified as follows:
\begin{align*}
\int_{\mathcal{W}} d(\boldsymbol{X}, \boldsymbol{w}) g_{\boldsymbol{\delta}}(\boldsymbol{w} \mid \boldsymbol{X}) \, d\boldsymbol{w}
&= \boldsymbol{\gamma}^{\top} \mathbb{E}_{g_{\boldsymbol{\delta}}}\left[\boldsymbol{\mu}_{u\mid w,x}\mid \boldsymbol{X}\right] \\
&= \boldsymbol{\gamma}^{\top} \boldsymbol{B}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{B}\boldsymbol{B}^{\top}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{w\mid u})^{-1} \mathbb{E}_{g_{\boldsymbol{\delta}}}\left[\boldsymbol{W}-h(\boldsymbol{X})\mid \boldsymbol{X}\right].
\end{align*}
It will also help to re-write $\boldsymbol{\gamma}$ as the following:
$$
\boldsymbol{\gamma}
=\sqrt{\mathrm{Var}(Y \mid \boldsymbol{W}, \boldsymbol{X})\cdot R^2_{Y \sim \boldsymbol{U} \mid \boldsymbol{W}, \boldsymbol{X}}}\ \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{u\mid w}^{-1/2}\boldsymbol{u}_0,
\qquad \|\boldsymbol{u}_0\|_2=1.
$$
We can now bound the absolute bias as
\begin{align*}
\left| \int_{\mathcal{W}} d(\boldsymbol{X}, \boldsymbol{w}) g_{\boldsymbol{\delta}}(\boldsymbol{w} \mid \boldsymbol{X}) \, d\boldsymbol{w} \right|
\le
\sqrt{\mathrm{Var}(Y \mid \boldsymbol{W}, \boldsymbol{X})\cdot R^2_{Y \sim \boldsymbol{U} \mid \boldsymbol{W}, \boldsymbol{X}}}\ 
\left\| \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{u\mid w}^{-1/2} \boldsymbol{B}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{B}\boldsymbol{B}^{\top}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{w\mid u})^{-1}
\mathbb{E}_{g_{\boldsymbol{\delta}}}\left[\boldsymbol{W}-h(\boldsymbol{X})\mid \boldsymbol{X}\right]
\right\|_2.
\end{align*}
This is a fully identifiable quantity once we have identified $\boldsymbol{B}$ up to rotation. This allows us to bound the confounding bias with only a single sensitivity parameter, $R^2_{Y \sim \boldsymbol{U} \mid \boldsymbol{W}, \boldsymbol{X}}$, as opposed to the two sensitivity components from the previous subsection.
